Recall
Recall is DayCache's memory retrieval feature. Users can ask natural language questions about their journal history and receive answers grounded in their own past entries. It uses RAG — the question is converted to a vector embedding, semantically similar journal chunks are retrieved, and Claude answers using those chunks as context. Recall maintains conversation history within a session so users can ask follow-up questions. It never invents — every answer is sourced from what the user actually wrote.
Examples: "What was I stressed about last month?" "When did I first mention wanting to change jobs?" "How has my mood been this year?"

Reflect
Reflect is DayCache's guided journaling feature. Instead of the user sitting down to write, the diary initiates a short conversational interview — asking questions about the user's day, listening to their answers, and writing a structured journal entry on their behalf. The user reviews and approves the generated entry before it is saved. Reflect is triggered by the user opening the feature; the system asks 4–6 contextual questions, synthesises the conversation into a first-person entry, and presents a preview. Nothing is saved without explicit user approval.
Examples of what Reflect asks: "How did today go?" "What was the most significant moment?" "How are you feeling right now?"
